The Federal Government has reassured its commitment to supporting volunteering activities and harnessing its resources for socio-economic development of the country. Permanent Secretary, Political and Economic Affairs Office, Office of the Secretary To The Government of The Federation (OSGF), Mr Andrew Adejo, stated this at Abagana, Anambra State at the closing ceremony of the State Association World Wide (ASA-World) free medical outreach. Adejo, represented by Emmanuel Agodi, said government’s support services to the association through its Nigerian National Volunteer Service Department (NNVS) would go a long way to enhancing good health and productivity. He said, “We have been encouraging volunteer groups and associations to offer their efforts and services to complement the government’s developmental efforts.   Black soot: Wike orders police, others to arrest, prosecute…     GAIN: Diaspora group lauds initiative, urges deployment in…     Sudan coup: UN to launch talks aimed at ending crisis   “It is understood that ASA-World has been undertaking this programme annually as part of its contribution to the development of Anambra State and the Department usually render support to ensure the programme is conducted successfully.” - Advertisement - While lamenting global health challenges, especially the ravaging Covid-19 pandemic, Adejo charged voluntary organizations to synergize for health service delivery to the people in rural communities. In a remark, member representing Njikoka, Anaocha and Dunukofia Federal Constituency, Hon Dozie Nwankwo,  praised the association for embarking on various humanitarian services for the people of the state. He pledged to always support the lifesaving initiative. Earlier, Leader of ASA-World, Dr Nwachukwu Anakwenze, said the group considered it proper to touch lives of the less privileged by providing free access to health care.